set up data:

country_trust <- read_csv("data/clean_country-fake-news-concern.csv")
Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  country = [31mcol_character()[39m,
  not_at_all_concerned = [32mcol_double()[39m,
  not_very_concerned = [32mcol_double()[39m,
  somewhat_concered = [32mcol_double()[39m,
  very_concerned = [32mcol_double()[39m,
  extremely_concerned = [32mcol_double()[39m,

country_trust_stack <- country_trust %>% select(country, somewhat_concered, total_concerned, total_not_concerned) %>% gather(concern, percent, somewhat_concered, total_concerned, total_not_concerned)
just_US <- country_trust_stack %>% filter(country == "US")

Small multiples to look at: Q_FAKE_NEWS_2_6. To what extent, if at all, are you concerned about the following: - The use of the term fake news (e.g. by politicians, others) to discredit news media they don’t like

test plot with USA:

US_trust <- ggplot(just_US, aes(reorder(concern, percent), percent)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Level of concern over the term fake news in each country surveyed", y = "level of concern", x = "percent", caption = "Source: Reuters 2018 Digital News Report") +
  #facet_wrap(~ country) + 
  theme_minimal()
US_trust

small multiples:

all_countries <- ggplot(country_trust_stack, aes(reorder(concern, percent), percent)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") + 
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Level of concern over the term fake news in each country surveyed", y = "level of concern", x = "percent", caption = "Source: Reuters 2018 Digital News Report") +
  facet_wrap(~ country) + 
  theme_minimal()
all_countries
